  "prompt": "Why is cellphone called as cellphone?",
  "response": "The term \"cellphone\" is derived from the way the technology is structured, specifically relating to the concept of \"cells\" in a cellular network. A cellular network divides a geographic area into smaller regions, or \"cells,\" each served by its own antenna or cell tower. When a call is made or data is transmitted via a cellphone, the signal is transferred from one cell to another as the user moves, ensuring continuity of the service.\n\nThe \"cell\" in \"cellphone\" thus refers to these individual cells that together form the network that allows for wireless communication. This system was a significant advancement over previous mobile radio systems because it enabled more efficient use of radio frequencies and allowed for a greater number of simultaneous conversations.",
